@page "/fill"

<div class="container mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Image Fill Mode</h1>
    <p class="mb-8">
        The `Fill` prop allows an image to fill its parent element. This is useful for responsive layouts where you want the image to take up the full space of its
        container.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div class="border p-4 rounded-lg">
            <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Fill with object-cover</h2>
            <div class="relative w-full h-100">
                <Image Src="/images/horse.jpg"
                       Alt="Fill image with object-cover"
                       Fill="true"
                       CssClass="rounded-md object-cover"
                       Caption="Fill image with object-cover"
                       Priority="true"
                       EnableDeveloperMode="true"/>
            </div>
            <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-gray-600">
                The image fills the container while maintaining its aspect ratio and covering the entire area. Some parts of
                the image may be cropped.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="border p-4 rounded-lg">
            <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Fill with object-contain</h2>
            <div class="relative h-80  ">
                <Image Src="/images/horse.jpg"
                       Alt="Fill image with object-contain"
                       Fill="true"
                       CssClass="rounded-md object-contain"
                       Caption="Fill image with object-contain"
                       Priority="true"
                       EnableDeveloperMode="true"/>
            </div>
            <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-gray-600">
                The image is contained within the container while maintaining its aspect ratio. The entire image is visible,
                but there may be empty space.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Code Example</h2>
        <pre class="bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-md overflow-x-auto">
        <code>
@("<")div class="relative w-full h-100"@(">")
    @("<")Image Src="/hero-image.jpg"
            Alt="Fill mode image"
		    Fill="true" // Set to true to enable fill mode
            class="object-cover" // or object-contain
    @("/>")
@("</")div@(">")
 </code>
        </pre>
    </div>
</div>


<div class="container mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Responsive Images</h1>
    <p class="mb-8">
        Using the sizes prop, you can tell browsers what size the image will be at different breakpoints. This helps the
        browser select the right image source from the automatically generated srcSet.
    </p>

    <div class="border p-4 rounded-lg">
        <div class="relative">
            <Image Src="/images/sky.jpg"
                   Alt="Responsive image"
                   Fill="true"
                   CssClass="rounded-md w-full h-auto" />
        </div>
        <div class="mt-4 text-sm text-gray-600">
            <p class="font-medium">How the sizes prop works:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 mt-2">
                <li>Defults Sizes is 100vw</li>
                <li>Browser selects the most appropriate image source based on these sizes</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="border p-4 rounded-lg">
        <div class="relative">
            <Image Src="/images/sky.jpg"
                   Alt="Sky"
                   Fill="true"
                   Sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, (max-width: 1024px) 50vw, 33vw"
                   CssClass="w-full h-auto"
                   Caption="Sky Fill" />

        </div>
        <div class="mt-4 text-sm text-gray-600">
            <p class="font-medium">How the sizes prop works:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 mt-2">
                <li>On mobile (up to 640px): Image takes full width (100vw)</li>
                <li>On tablets (640px-1024px): Image takes half the width (50vw)</li>
                <li>On desktop (>1024px): Image takes one-third of the width (33vw)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Code Example</h2>
        <pre class="bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-md overflow-x-auto">
@("<")Image
      Src="/responsive-image.jpg"
      Alt="Responsive image"
      Width="1200"
      Height="800"
	  Sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, (max-width: 1200px) 50vw, 33vw" // default is 100vw
      CssClass="w-full h-auto"
@("/>")
        </pre>
    </div>
</div>